Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` and use `Shell.Current.GoToAsync` only if confirmed:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget the async prompt; return true to cancel navigation
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // cancels the default back navigation
    }
}
```

> `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the **hardware/software back button** (Android back gesture, etc.). Returning `true` cancels the navigation.

**3. Replace the Shell back arrow with a "Cancel" button:**

In your XAML, set `Shell.BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            IconOverride=""
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        return;
    }

    bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
        "Unsaved Changes",
        "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
        "Discard", "Stay");

    if (leave)
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- `OnBackButtonPressed` covers the **system back** gesture/button.
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` covers the **toolbar back** button and lets you customize its text/icon.
- You need both because `BackButtonBehavior.Command` does **not** trigger `OnBackButtonPressed`, and vice versa.
- Setting `IconOverride=""` hides the arrow so only "Cancel" text shows.
